      {
        "heading": "Types of Cells: Prokaryotic vs. Eukaryotic",
        "explanation": "All living organisms are made of cells, but they fall into two main categories based on their internal structure.",
        "keyPoints": [
          "Prokaryotes have no nucleus (e.g., Bacteria).",
          "Eukaryotes have a true nucleus with membrane (e.g., Plants/Animals).",
          "The word 'Eu' means true, and 'Karyon' means kernel/nucleus."
        ],
        "examples": [
          "Bacterial cells are prokaryotic.",
          "Human cheek cells or onion peel cells are eukaryotic."
        ],
        "whyItMatters": "This distinction helps scientists classify all life on Earth and understand evolutionary complexity.",
        "terminology": [
          "Prokaryote",
          "Eukaryote"
        ],
        "detailedExplanation": "In Prokaryotes, the genetic material (DNA) floats freely in the cytoplasm without a boundary. In Eukaryotes, DNA is safely stored inside a nucleus surrounded by a membrane.",
