  "introduction": "\"Imagine you have a magnifying glass. If you look at a piece of cork, what do you see? Tiny boxes! In 1665, Robert Hooke saw exactly this under his microscope. He didn't know it yet, but he had just discovered the 'brick' that builds every living thing on Earth—from the smallest bacteria to the tallest tree and even us! Today, we unlock the story of how cells were found and learn why they are split into two main families: Prokaryotes and Eukaryotes.\"",
  "theory": {
    "overview": "Cells are the fundamental units of life. The study began with Robert Hooke's observation of cork in 1665, leading to the classification of cells based on their internal complexity.",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Robert Hooke discovered cells in 1665 using a microscope.",
      "He observed dead cell walls in cork slices.",
      "Cells are classified as Prokaryotic (no nucleus) or Eukaryotic (true nucleus)."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "The concept of the 'cell' revolutionized biology. Before Hooke, life was not understood at a microscopic level. When he examined cork, he saw empty compartments which were actually dead cell walls. This led to the term 'Cell'. Later scientists realized that all living things are made of cells (Cell Theory). The most critical distinction in modern biology is between Prokaryotes and Eukaryotes. Prokaryotic cells (like bacteria) are simpler, lacking a nuclear membrane, meaning their DNA floats freely. Eukaryotic cells (plants, animals, fungi) have a complex structure with a defined nucleus holding the genetic material, allowing for more specialized functions."
  },
